What is this judgment before God that we will face?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now, this judgement and purging of our last remains of our sinful natures likely won't be pleasant. We will be faced with all the times we disappointed God. So, the process might be &quot;painful&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Where in the Bible does it say this will happen?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>God is completely capable of hearing our prayer, hoping that a persons suffering in Purgatory is lessened. God can then go and ensure that the persons suffering will have been lessened.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Where does the Bible say that those who belong to Christ will be forced to suffer for their sins after death?  Honestly, that sounds sacreligious to me - it totally defeats what Christ did on the cross.  Suddenly, Christ's suffering for us and His sacrifice was not enough.  I will end up having to pay for my sins in some form because Christ's blood wasn't enough.  Sorry, I refuse to accept this and believe it to be totally against the Bible.  Jesus sacrifice for us was perfect and complete.  He suffered for us so that we would not.  Why would He force us to suffer when He suffered in our place?  That makes absolutely no sense.  I can't even put into words what you're making God sound like. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   This sounds a lot like mormonism to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Have you ever passed an accident scene and prayed something like &quot;Dear Lord, I pray that everyone involved in the accident is ok.&quot; That's praying for something in the past - to us. I have even heard Protestants pray for the recently deceased who they don't think had accepted God and they say &quot;Lord, I pray that Mr. X accepted Jesus before his death&quot;. Not much different from the Pugatory thing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well here's one protestant who doesn't pray for things in the past because I know what's past is past. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
