<br>
Thanks for addressing this question from the Bible, while<br>
refraining from leaning on the deutero-canonical books.<br>
(Or whatever they're called.)<br>
<br>
I'm familiar with the verses you cited. <br>
My understanding of them is far different from the one<br>
you cited, however.<br>
<br>
If they reflect a concept that we simply tack the name<br>
&quot;purgatory&quot; to, then I have no problem accepting the concept<br>
of purgatory.   However, I do not believe they in any way<br>
reflect that.  <br>
<br>
I'm not sure if it would be good to get into the whole<br>
&quot;Judgement Day&quot; subject at this place and time.<br>
However, the I Corinthians 15 verses, to me, seem to refer<br>
to specific events as yet in the future.   The same with<br>
the &quot;trial by fire&quot;,which, if I understand correctly, is the<br>
closest section of Scripture to what you are describing.<br>
<br>
If it seems profitable to you, I'm not adverse to discussing<br>
them verse-by-verse and comparing out understanding<br>
with the texts-or at least the modern versions and the <br>
Stephens Text, which I can grab fairly easy at times.<br>
<br>
If it does not seem profitable to you, we can just forget<br>
about it and love each other as brothers anyway.<br>
(Or scorn each other, as the manner of some is.)<br>
<br>
Let me know what you think will profit the good group. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Your Friendly<br>Orthodox Resource</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/9/03 2:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> By saying the Catholics added books, that demanded a response because that is just not true.  Just as this statement is myth as well:  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Oh, that the catholic church forbid people to own a copy of the Bible and could only know the scriptures by priests reading it. Yeah, I remember reading about that one.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Where is the historical underpinning of that statement?  True not very many individuals owned a copy of scriptures prior to the printing press as the cost was out of reach for all but the very rich.  But that does not mean they were forbidden to read it.<br>
