<br>
What history did you study? &quot;The Great Controversy Ended&quot; by Ellen White? What is really, really sad is that you are propogating this unhistorical anti-Catholic lie. <br>
<br>
If this is your retort to the fact that the Old Testament canon of the Christians included the deuterocanonical books I feel sorry and embarrased for the whole of protestantism.  <br>
<br>
Here is what some Protestant/Catholic/Jewish scholars think about the closing of the canon:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>J.P. Lewis:“That the Old Testament canon was not completed until the Christian era is recognized by all critical scholars today, and many suggest that the rivalry offered by Christian books was a spur for the closing of the Jewish canon.”<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Menachem Cohen: “the motives behind the struggle were, apparently, ideological and polemical, aimed at deviant groups (Christians, Samaritans) who had adopted these text-types;”<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Sundberg:“Writing about 90 C.E., Josephus gives us the first glimpse of a nearly finished Jewish canon.”<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The Pontifical Biblical Commission: “When Judaism came to close its own canon, the Christian Church was<br>
sufficiently independent from Judaism not to be immediately affected. It was only at a later period that a closed Hebrew canon began to exert influence on how Christians viewed it.”<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It is without any scholarly doubt that the early Christian community used the Septuagint (LXX) which included the deuterocanonical books. Even the original 1611 KJV included them in an appendix.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You're really trying my patience. All I said was that I was refraining from making a comment to it. I said nothing to argue it. So I see your posting the same thing again as an attempt to provoke me into commenting. My opinion would be rather strong and I really don't want to get into the issue. So let's just drop it. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Jeff...ie. read between the lines: Catholics and Orthodox are not Christians.<br>
<br>
If being familiar with history makes Catholics and Orthodox not Christian, well then I am not Christian by your definition of the word.<br>
<br>
But isn't that what the convert John Henry Cardinal Newman wrote: &quot;To know history is to cease being Protestant.&quot;<br>
