<br>
I agree that God is neither limited by time nor space. <br>
(I can cite the verses, but since we agree, it seems<br>
 unnecessary.)<br>
<br>
It's a separate question as to whether or not God wants<br>
US to operate in a linear timeframe.<br>
The evidence seems to support that He DOES want us to<br>
operate in a linear fashion.<br>
<br>
I say that because I accept the omniscience of God and <br>
believe He knows how it all will turn out, but believe He does<br>
not tell us all of it, thereby allowing us to retain our freewill.<br>
<br>
There are Christians out there who DON'T accept this, and<br>
they're the ones who doubt God's omniscience.<br>
<br>
However, God's choosing to deal with us in a linear fashion<br>
explains how God gives us a warning, and, when we heed it,<br>
we &quot;change what would happen&quot;.  The fastest example of<br>
this is the Book of Jonah.  Jonah warned of the judgement of<br>
God, the people repented, and the judgement was stayed.<br>
This was NOT a surprise to God, but He didn't tell Jonah<br>
&quot;the people will definitely repent, so this is just a warning.&quot;<br>
He allowed Jonah and the people to make their own <br>
decisions.<br>
<br>
I'm confident God COULD do whatever, whenever. <br>
Asking me to pray for the past, however, is NOT something I<br>
see in the commonly-accepted canon. <br>
Further, I'm not convinced God altering the past would not be<br>
breaking His own rules of reality-allowing events to unfold<br>
in a linear fashion.  <br>
I'm suspicious of the entire subject as an interpolation of<br>
gnostic thought into Christianity.  I'm not afraid to discuss<br>
it, just leery of subscribing to it without what I consider<br>
sufficient evidence. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
